      <p>Liverpool City Council commission The Whitechapel Centre to provide a co-ordinated response via a <em>“Somewhere safe to stay Hub”</em>, Labre House. This provision is delivered 365 nights a year and offers shelter and support every night, including when temperatures drop or severe weather events are predicted.</p>

      <h2 class="h2">Where is the centre?</h2>

      <p>Labre House is situated in Camden Street in Liverpool City Centre. The service is open from 8pm -8am every night of the year including any periods when SWEP is predicted. Access into the service can be via self-referral at Whitechapel Centre day hub service, situated at Lansdale Street, Liverpool or via Always Room Inside helpline <a href="tel:03001232041">0300 123 2041</a> 24 hours a day delivered by Whitechapel’s Rough Sleeper team.  The helpline is for either individuals facing imminent risk of rough sleeping in Liverpool,  or for members of the public who are concerned about a rough sleeper, street outreach teams and or faith groups and any other agency in the city supporting any individual who is rough sleeping.</p>

      <h2 class="h2">When is the Provision Open & What is Offered?</h2>

      <p>Labre house is open to Rough Sleepers from 8pm -8am and the following support is offered;</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Safe shelter, warmth and support</li>
        <li>Support to access accommodation, advice and signposting to Health, Substance Misuse services, Benefits agencies and other support agencies.</li>
        <li>Bedding and storage of belongings</li>
        <li>Dogs and pets are welcome</li>
        <li>Couples welcome</li>
        <li>Onsite food and hot drinks during stay</li>
        <li>Friendly skilled staff to support any individual</li>
        <li>Anyone with No Recourse To Public Funds will also be assessed.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="h2">Who can access?</h2>

      <p>The provision is for rough sleepers or anyone who finds themselves rough sleeping that night in Liverpool. The service aims to be as inclusive as possible and will manage risk on a case by cases basis to ensure the most entrenched and excluded individuals are able to gain shelter and support.</p>

      <h2 class="h2">How will agencies and people sleeping rough know when the centre is open?</h2>

      <p>The Whitechapel Centre and Liverpool City Council promote the service all year round as well as Whitechapel Centre’s Rough Sleeper Team who ensure that all rough sleepers are aware of service via street outreach. The Rough Sleeper team also promote service to all local providers and agencies.</p>
      <p>Adverts are also made via <a href="https://whitechapelcentre.co.uk">Whitechapel’s Website</a>, <a href="https://liverpool.gov.uk">Liverpool City Council</a> and other social media platforms such as Facebook and Twitter.  The Always Room Inside helpline is also publicised through a public marketing plan e.g. bus stops, taxis etc.</p>
